          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-bereft-bewildered-and-eager-to-remember-73aca8da?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">儿童读物：<strong>失落、困惑和渴望记住</strong></a></h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-bereft-bewildered-and-eager-to-remember-73aca8da"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832047?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption">琳达·舒特 (Linda Shute) 绘制的《提醒我》<span class="wsj-article-credit">尼尔·波特 (Neal Porter)</span>插图</div></div></div><p>对《西尔维斯特的信》、《提醒我》、《也许是鲸鱼》、《寻找巨型北极水母》和《放射性蜘蛛来了》的评论。<em>梅根·考克斯·格登的评论</em></p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-bereft-bewildered-and-eager-to-remember-73aca8da?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-women-in-tennis-3ecef071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">五佳：论网球界的女性</a></h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-women-in-tennis-3ecef071"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832581?width=700&amp;height=469" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">美联社</span></div></div></div><p>由《宫廷女王：网球传奇爱丽丝·马布尔的众多人生》一书的作者玛德琳·布莱斯 (Madeleine Blais) 评选。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-women-in-tennis-3ecef071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读文章</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p><em>将精彩的阅读推荐发送到您的收件箱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=410&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">订阅</a>每周的图书时事通讯。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 20:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75<category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Bee Sting’ Review: When Did It All Go Wrong?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在保罗·默里的小说中，一个富裕的家庭的地毯被拔掉了。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140174222239584"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833512?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140174222239584"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-sacks" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨姆·萨克斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 4:03（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>保罗·默里在他的长篇小说《蜂蜇》中讲述了爱尔兰本土红松鼠的悲伤故事。一个多世纪前，白金汉公爵向爱尔兰乡村庄园的一对新婚夫妇送了一个柳条篮，里面装有十几只北美灰松鼠。当礼篮在草坪上被隆重地打开时，松鼠们就冲进了森林。很快，“就像殖民主义的寓言一样”，它们在整个岛上繁殖起来。灰松鼠携带松鼠痘病毒，但对其免疫，这种病毒会使红松鼠的嘴周围出现病变，使它们无法进食。就这样，因为一份结婚礼物，整个物种被推向灭绝的边缘。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/3e98949a-0a13-451e-86b6-aed43c023259.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>巴尼斯家族是默里先生家族传奇中遭受灾难困扰的爱尔兰本土家族。从外表上看，他们是这座无名小城市羡慕的对象。迪基是一家家长，经营着从父亲那里继承的当地汽车经销店，并一直住在他儿时的房子里，后院有一片巨大的林地。他的妻子伊梅尔达是一位著名的美女，她像武术黑带一样挥舞着信用卡。他们的孩子 Cass 和 PJ 在物质条件优越的情况下长大。这是一次完美的国内伊卡洛斯飞行，让坠机坠落到地球上。</p><p>造成这一切的原因是2008年银行业危机后的爱尔兰经济萧条，导致迪基的经销店濒临破产，并迫使伊梅尔达在 eBay 上出售她的名牌服装，这是一种耻辱。财务崩溃对家庭成员来说是一种违约行为——正如 PJ 所说，“缓慢而有条不紊地破坏了他认为真实的一切”——并使他们对以前认为理所当然的行为产生了深深的怀疑。伊梅尔达抱怨某种长期存在的人格缺陷，导致迪基被动地接受自己的毁灭。卡斯承诺进入三一学院的入学资格现在面临风险，她开始想知道她的父母还隐瞒了什么。为什么披风上的家庭照片中没有结婚照？酒吧里那个醉酒的老家伙说伊梅尔达曾经和迪基死去的弟弟弗兰克订婚，这是什么意思？</p><p>随着《蜜蜂蜇伤》继续巴尼斯夫妇的故事，它开始解开过去的事件，通过模糊的因果关系向后移动，就像倒转的多米诺骨牌视频一样。 “当你回顾过去时，你无法判断自己究竟错在哪里，”迪基认为。 “这是一次失误吗？”本书所探讨的问题是为什么事情会这样发生。每个家庭的背景中是否都存在某种原罪，预示着堕落的到来，松鼠被释放、未来被决定的决定性时刻？另一本书可能会通过调查命运或机会来探索这个谜团，但《蜂蜇》是一部爱尔兰小说，充满了迷信和预言（伊梅尔达的阿姨罗丝会读茶叶，并且有“闪现”的千里眼），所以这个问题更好措辞：有诅咒之类的东西吗？ </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 15 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>乔治·奥威尔的婚姻、早期好莱坞明星不可思议的生活、改变美国民间音乐的人等等。</p></div></div><p> To note that this novel is Irish is to call up another, more flattering generalization: stylistically it&#39;s outstanding, defined by supple, engaging prose and a preternatural sense for storytelling. Even keeping in mind the marvels of 20th-century Irish literature, the quality of the writing still emerging from this small island is a source of wonder. Four Irish authors, including Mr. Murray, have just been named on the longlist of the Booker Prize, which is open to English-language fiction from anywhere in the world. The country&#39;s roll call of talent—Anne Enright, Kevin Barry, Sara Baume, Donal Ryan, Eimear McBride, John Banville, Claire-Louis Bennett, Sebastian Barry, Claire Keegan, Colm Tóibín, Emma Donoghue and Bernard MacLaverty, to provide an incomplete list—is also notably diverse, encompassing updates to a glorious literary tradition as well as a thriving avant-garde.</p><p> Mr. Murray&#39;s place in all this appears to be evolving. Until “The Bee Sting” it would have made sense to call him Ireland&#39;s best comic novelist, based on his hilarious and macabre boarding-school romp “Skippy Dies” (2010) and to a lesser extent “The Mark and the Void” (2015), a sharp banking satire undermined a little by narrative gimmicks. But the new novel, while frequently funny, has more serious intentions. Mr. Murray has always been able to dazzle and entertain, but he has never before developed characters with this much depth or capacity for tragedy.</p><p> So richly detailed is “The Bee Sting” that it reads like four books woven into one, as each member of the Barnes family is allotted a lengthy section rendered in free indirect discourse. Cass, in her final year of high school, is mostly preoccupied with staying in the good graces of her popular and controlling best friend, Elaine, and Mr. Murray nicely meshes together the elements of disillusion, peer pressure and sexual awakening that mark her troubled maturation. PJ, who is younger and more cerebral, is mostly left to his own devices and his section takes the form of a thriller: Menaced by a bully, he considers running away to Dublin to stay with a friend he met online and who, it&#39;s obvious to the reader, is a predatory adult masquerading as a child.</p><p> The novel plunges fully into the past when it occupies the mind of Imelda. Mr. Murray has borrowed from Molly Bloom&#39;s soliloquy in “Ulysses” in imagining this earthy character, whose thoughts are rendered without punctuation (though capital letters still indicate the start of new sentences, so the chapters are not hard to read). Imelda, who has “an accent that could strip paint,” comes from poverty and violence, the only daughter of a tyrannical former boxer, and her courtship with Frank, a Gaelic football star and the golden child of the affluent Barnes family, is her means of escape. When Frank dies in a car crash—he is buried in his wedding suit—Imelda is tossed back into uncertainty until she grabs the life vest offered by an equally dazed and grief-stricken Dickie.</p><p> Has Dickie acted manfully, stepping into his brother&#39;s shoes in marriage and the family business, or is his substitution a violation of the natural order? The chapters from his point of view cast back to his university days, and while they ought not to be spoiled here, they introduce more secrets that his seemingly covetable family life is meant to hide. A complex and highly rewarding sense of ambiguity begins to attach to the plot turns as these secrets are threatened with exposure. A terrible feeling of inevitability continues to bear down on the Barneses, promising their dissolution, but it&#39;s also clear that they are complicit in choosing and persisting on their paths and that a transformative act of honesty could change their outcomes.</p><p> Through a succession of suspenseful twists and feints, Mr. Murray advances the stories of the characters individually and then collectively, in a bravura final section that draws all four together. It&#39;s only in a final <em>coup</em> <em>de theatre</em> , when coincidences bring about a literal four-way collision, that the drama feels heavy-handed, manipulated rather than organically unfolding.</p><p> But by this point, we have spent so much time with the characters that our investment in their lives has been vouchsafed. The nice thing about this novel&#39;s somewhat 19th-century length is that is allows for moments of reality outside the chain of causation that propels everyone forward. Startling flashes of sympathy tear through the curtains of secrecy and self-involvement. Considering the fragility of fatherhood, Dickie thinks: “You couldn&#39;t protect the people you loved—that was the lesson of history, and it struck him therefore that to love someone meant to be opened up to a radically heightened level of suffering.” Later, in a rare access of concern for her younger brother, Cass comes to the same realization: “This must be what it&#39;s like being a parent, constantly worrying your kids will be annihilated the moment you look away. That must be why they&#39;re all so insane.” In the faltering mixture of candor and deception, helplessness and desperate prevention, Mr. Murray creates a heightened but truthful portrait of family love.</p><p> And what about that strange absence of wedding photos? The explanation Cass hears is that, as Imelda drove to the church, a bee got trapped behind her veil and stung her below the eye, leaving a welt that her vanity wouldn&#39;t allow to be recorded. Cass, in a teenaged snit, takes the story as evidence of how ridiculous her parents are and a portent for their failures. The real reason, gradually revealed across the course of “The Bee Sting,” turns out to be more complicated, more human and much more awful. Which should they choose: Continue on inside the maze of a consoling lie, or accept the painful consequences—and maybe the freedom—of telling things as they really are?</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Sacks is the Journal&#39;s fiction critic.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 20:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d<author><![CDATA[Sam Sacks]]></author><category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Romantic’ Review: Scenes of a Century]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> William Boyd&#39;s panoramic novel takes in Napoleon&#39;s last stand, terror in Sri Lanka and a chat with Lord Byron. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140232817348898"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833545?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Villa Diodati in Geneva, engraving by William Purser.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: G. Dagli Orti/Bridgeman Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140232817348898"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Brooke Allen</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 3:54 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a-century-fc855e30"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Beginning with his first novel, “A Good Man in Africa,” William Boyd has built a reputation over the course of more than four decades as a purveyor of reliably literate, enjoyable commercial fiction, often set in attractive historical or geographical milieux. His latest work, “The Romantic,” like several of its predecessors including the popular “Any Human Heart,” is what Mr. Boyd himself has dubbed a “whole-life novel”: a cradle-to-grave account of its protagonist and, necessarily, a portrait of the era he lived through. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/dc3c8cb1-8a29-4235-8fb6-02804ed85976.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “Any Human Heart,” along with “Sweet Caress” and “The New Confessions,” took their central characters through the 20th century, native territory for their author. With “The Romantic,” though, Mr. Boyd goes back to the 19th. Cashel Greville Ross, the illegitimate son of an Irish landowner, is born at the very end of the 1700s. During the course of a long life he witnesses some of the most dramatic scenes of his century. He sees action at Waterloo, observes a massacre during the Third Kandyan War in Sri Lanka, gallivants through Italy with Byron and the Shelleys (he even helps Byron cremate Shelley&#39;s corpse on the beach at Viareggio), meets—and loses—the love of his life (Contessa Raphaella Rezzo) in Ravenna, does time as a Grub Street author in London, farms the land near Concord, Mass. (Mr. Boyd surprisingly resists the temptation to have his hero rub shoulders with the neighboring Transcendentalists), goes to Africa in search of the source of the Nile where he meets Richard Burton and runs afoul of John Hanning Speke, becomes Nicaraguan consul in Trieste (don&#39;t ask!) and ends his days in Venice, where he is buried on the Isola di San Michele. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> George Orwell&#39;s marriage, the unlikely life of an early Hollywood star, the man who changed American folk music and more.</p></div></div><p> All this should be fun. But alas, “The Romantic” is a tired, spiritless piece of work, written as if Mr. Boyd was slogging dutifully through the formula he created and has previously used to better effect. Part of the problem is that Ross has very little individuality. In a Guardian essay on the whole-life novel, Mr. Boyd claimed that the reader “comes to identify with the central character . 。 。 in a different, more engaged way because they have all the necessary information, significant and insignificant.” Well, we may have been given plenty of information about Ross&#39;s life, but the fact is that he&#39;s just too bland to identify with, and certainly too bland to suffice as a long novel&#39;s throughline. “Who was he?” Ross muses about himself at one point. “What was he? What was the &#39;were&#39; that constituted his present &#39;are&#39;?” The answer, not that we care too much, is that Ross is simply a literary gimmick used to tie together various carefully researched historical set pieces.</p><p> Novels like “The Sot-Weed Factor” (John Barth) and “Mason &amp; Dixon” (Thomas Pynchon) can be irritating, with their authors&#39; torturous and self-conscious efforts to work historical language and currents of thought into their personal styles. Mr. Boyd doesn&#39;t even give it a try. Ross and his many friends and associates basically speak modern English with the occasional period word like “withal” thrown in. “With respect, sir,” Ross at one point says to his superior officer. “Since when were you an expert on Kandyan mores?” In dialogue, a totally anachronistic expression like “money for jam” (coined during World War I) will pop up from time to time—not as an authorial in-joke but apparently because Mr. Boyd couldn&#39;t be bothered to come up with something a person of the 19th century might actually have said. And what about this, uttered by Ross? “Good grief. Byron in Pisa. Who&#39;d have thought?”真的吗？ Sometimes the narrative progresses from 20th-century locutions—bad enough—to those of the 21st, as when the Shelley circle is referred to as “these privileged people.” As Ross would say, Good grief!</p><p> The fact that Mr. Boyd has selected for his cast of characters three of the most famous talkers of the 19th century—Byron, Shelley and Burton—and then given them hardly any dialogue is indicative of how half-hearted this novel is. One can understand that it must be intimidating for a modern writer to invent dialogue for legendary geniuses, but wouldn&#39;t there be at least a little bit of fun in trying? Instead, Mr. Boyd takes the easy way out by simply describing these famous characters&#39; manners of speech. “Burton talked and talked, exhausting everyone . 。 。 Cashel slipped away. He imagined Burton haranguing the salt-cellar and the empty decanter of port, perfectly happy to have them as an audience. He was clearly an intelligent man, fiercely intelligent—but to be confined in a room with him . 。 .” One can believe it, from what one knows of Burton&#39;s personality; but a novelist with spirit wouldn&#39;t back down from the challenge.</p><p> Since at every stop in this picaresque tale the author always has his sights doggedly set on his hero&#39;s next destination, promising characters and situations crop up only to be unceremoniously dumped a few pages on. Ross&#39;s complicated relationship with his father, Sir Guy Stillwell, starts out being interesting, but by the time Sir Guy dies he seems to have been no more meaningful in his son&#39;s life than anyone else in the passing parade. A couple of the literary Londoners Ross meets during his writing career—the <em>salonnière</em> Ethalinda Davenport and the crooked publisher Purvis Yelverton—are excellent, but they&#39;re all too soon left behind. An idyll that Ross enjoys with Byron&#39;s paramour Claire Clairmont offers exciting possibilities, but it fizzles and Ross moves on. Occasionally Mr. Boyd touches on what it might really feel like to have taken part in 19th-century life, as when Ross returns to Britain after a long absence and is struck by the revolutionary implications of railroad travel: “It had all become &#39;normal&#39; with astonishing speed.” But these are passing moments.</p><p> Who is Mr. Boyd&#39;s target reader, one wonders? Anyone with a genuine interest in the Byron and Shelley circle, or African exploration, or literary London, will find nothing of consequence in these pages. And anyone looking for an engrossing love story will not find one in the conventional romance of Ross and his Raphaella. The novel might serve as a novice&#39;s introduction to the period, a sort of 19th Century 101. But for an author of Mr. Boyd&#39;s reputation, that&#39;s a low bar to set.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。 Allen is a frequent writer on books and the arts for the Journal. She teaches in the Prison Education Initiative of Bennington College.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 19:54:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a-century-fc855e30</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a-century-fc855e30<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> William Boyd</category><category> books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Finding W.H. Hudson’ Review: The Enigmatic Birdman]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The mysterious, contradictory life of the man who devoted himself to the preservation of England&#39;s birds. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140661223878380"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833372?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Detail of the portrait of WH Hudson by Frank Brooks that hangs above the fireplace at the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds headquarters in Sandy, England.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Conor Mark Jameson </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140661223878380"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Christoph Irmscher</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 3:45 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-w-h-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> William Henry Hudson (1841-1922), one of the founding members of the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds, must have been quite a sight when, perched high atop his Sunbeam bicycle, he roamed the English countryside in search of his beloved feathered friends. A beanpole of a man, decked out in tweeds, waistcoat and laced boots, looking more British than the British, he kept himself cool by carrying a moist handkerchief inside his hat. Some believed that Hudson, sharp-eyed and constantly on the move, was like a wild bird himself—a hawk, perhaps, or an eagle. His laugh sounded like that of the green woodpecker, reports Conor Mark Jameson in his new biography, adding that he could no longer listen to that bird without thinking of Hudson. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/5c97296d-3812-49f1-a3ab-57624157eade.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> During the 25 years that Mr. Jameson worked in the offices of the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds, a portrait of a binocular-wielding, squinty-eyed Hudson stared back at him silently from over a mantelpiece. A Cambridgeshire writer and conservationist, Mr. Jameson became determined to restore Hudson&#39;s voice. He combed through the archives for traces of his hero and meandered across Britain—sometimes on a bicycle himself—to re-create Hudson&#39;s travels (and was mightily pleased when he found a goldfinch exactly where Hudson had heard it too). The result is a sprightly, conversational book, sprinkled with autobiographical asides, a creative blend of detective work and narrative intuition (“we can only guess”), as hard to pin down as its subject. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> George Orwell&#39;s marriage, the unlikely life of an early Hollywood star, the man who changed American folk music and more.</p></div></div><p> If “Finding WH Hudson,” at the end, doesn&#39;t really “find” WH Hudson, that&#39;s par for the course. Hudson was a puzzle even to his closest friends. For starters, he wasn&#39;t really British. Born in Argentina to parents originally from the United States, Guillermo Enrique, as he was known to his neighbors, grew up on the Pampas surrounded by horses, sheep and herds of cattle, with a small library his only link to a world of cultural refinement. Hudson later burned much of his correspondence, but that hasn&#39;t kept the biographers from wondering about his reasons for emigrating to England in 1874. In his “Living in the Sound of the Wind” (2015), the model behind Mr. Jameson&#39;s efforts, the literary critic Jason Wilson asks the obvious question: Why would a professed nature enthusiast like Hudson decide to leave Argentina, a country with “enormous open spaces and a blue dome of sky and no pollution,” and settle in soot-blanketed, overcrowded London? To which Mr. Jameson adds the equally difficult-to-answer question that preoccupies him: Why would a South American naturalist, virtually from the moment of his arrival, become so passionately involved in efforts to save the wild birds of a country not his own?</p><p> Hudson&#39;s life abounded in contradictions. After he came to England, he threw himself into natural-history writing, producing a steady stream of the most beautiful descriptions of South American as well as domestic birds, conjuring “the overflowing gladness of the lark; the spirit of wildness of the black-cap; the airy, delicate tenderness of the willow-wren” (“British Birds,” 1895). But while Hudson remained adamant that he wasn&#39;t “one of you damned writers,” he became internationally known for a novel, “Green Mansions” (1904), in which a Venezuelan political refugee hiding in the woods falls madly in love with a birdlike jungle creature named Rima (things don&#39;t end well). Hudson&#39;s lush reverie was later made into a Hollywood movie with a lanky, unfailingly kempt Anthony Perkins alongside a pixyish Audrey Hepburn, who looks as if she had just popped in from her dressing room. Arguably, the fakeness had started even earlier: Hudson himself never set foot in the Venezuelan wilderness.</p><p> Hudson didn&#39;t make it easy for people to like him. Even before he came to England, he loudly criticized Darwin for assuming a certain species of South American woodpecker fed on the ground and never visited trees. Darwin adjusted the offending passage but also snarked at this disrespectful “fellow worker,” likely a disbeliever in evolution, who had so gratuitously attacked him. Mr. Jameson gives Hudson high marks for “his forthrightness” of approach but doesn&#39;t mention that Darwin turned out to be correct, after all—see Hudson&#39;s later, unapologetic admission in “Birds of La Plata” (1920).</p><p> Nevertheless, Hudson succeeded in attracting a large circle of devotees, and Mr. Jameson at times appears to be more interested in them than in Hudson himself. His book sparkles with skillfully drawn portraits of Hudson&#39;s female collaborators at the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds or of such friends as “Don Roberto,” the Scottish-Hispanic politician Cunninghame Graham, who enjoyed parading his horse, gaucho-style, in Hyde Park. We learn much, too, about the literati who admired him, including Joseph Conrad, John Galsworthy and Virginia Woolf. (Ezra Pound thought well enough of Hudson to put him in his “Cantos,” as “Huddy . . . taller than anyone present”). A Hudson superfan was the eccentric Margaret Brooke, the estranged wife of the rajah of the East Indian territory of Sarawak, who shared Hudson&#39;s twin passions for the tropics and ornithology: She would greet visitors to her Ascot mansion seated in a blue armchair, a green parrot attached to her wrist.</p><p> By the end of Mr. Jameson&#39;s impeccably researched book, Guillermo Enrique&#39;s secrets have been left mostly intact. For example, we still don&#39;t know what to make of his likely sexless marriage to his much older landlady Emily Wingrave, a former opera singer who barely reached up to his elbow, or of his affair (if indeed it was) with the journalist Linda Gardiner, the editor of Hudson&#39;s posthumously published “Rare, Vanishing, and Lost British Birds” (1923). It seems that WH Hudson himself was a bit of a lost bird, too.</p><p> We do know that Hudson came to regret his decision to leave his native country. “When I think of that land so rich in bird life,” he sighed in “Birds of La Plata,” “I probably made choice of the wrong road of the two then open to me.” But maybe it was precisely this experience of self-induced personal loss, of an opportunity given and then abandoned, that enabled him to be more attentive to losses of a different, larger kind—the disappearance of so many birds from British woods, fields and shores. Mr. Jameson aptly describes the passage of the 1921 Plumage Bill, banning the use of feathers in human clothes, as one of the highlights of Hudson&#39;s life.</p><p> “Finding WH Hudson” gets us close to its odd protagonist, though never closer than Hudson himself got to many of his birds. Recalling a time in his Argentinian youth when he stalked a little red heron (now the striated heron) into a bed of rushes, Hudson admits he at first couldn&#39;t locate the bird anywhere, only to discover, to his surprise, that it had been right next to him, a perfect imitation of a rush, neck and body frozen into an image of unassailable straightness. As Hudson circled around it, the bird turned, too, its motions corresponding exactly to Hudson&#39;s own even as it remained rigidly in place. The elusive Hudson had found his match in nature: “I could not finish admiring, and thought that never had anything so beautiful fallen in my way before.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Irmscher is the author of “The Poetics of Natural History,” available in a new edition with photographs by Rosamond Purcell.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 19:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-wh-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-wh-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> Royal Society for the Protection of Birds</category><category> books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>natural environment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Wifedom’ Review: A Portrait of Her Marriage]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> George Orwell&#39;s first wife played an undervalued role in his literary career—and saw a side of him that didn&#39;t always match his public image. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590138551244768456"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833555?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Eileen Orwell with her son, Richard, 1944.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: UCL Special Collections </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590138551244768456"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> Donna Rifkind</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 12:28 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wifedom-review-orwell-a-portrait-of-her-marriage-fb31ab2c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The short, urgent life of George Orwell owed much of its success to the devotion of his first wife, Eileen O&#39;Shaughnessy. For decades after her early death in 1945, scholars tended to overlook her importance in Orwell&#39;s story. Then, in 2005, six of her witty, detailed letters to a friend were discovered, providing fresh revelations about her nine-year marriage to one of the most beloved of 20th-century British authors. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a8b6e487-9520-40b7-a77c-357853604070.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The letters surfaced too late to inform the major Orwell biographies that had already appeared, though several more recent books use them to restore Eileen&#39;s significance. One of these, “Eileen: The Making of George Orwell,” by Sylvia Topp, was published in 2020 and is so scrupulously detailed that it makes another conventional biography of Eileen hard to justify. But “Wifedom,” by the Australian writer Anna Funder, is an entirely different enterprise.</p><p> Ms. Funder is a boundary-breaking, risk-taking writer whose previous books synthesized memoir, fact and imagination to impressive effect. “Stasiland: Stories From Behind the Berlin Wall” (2003) chronicled her post-1989 encounters with victims and perpetrators of the surveillance culture that dominated life in the East German dictatorship. “All That I Am” (2011), a historical novel set during the rise of Nazism, blended truth and fiction to dramatize the life of the anti-fascist German playwright Ernst Toller. Both books are nuanced, chilling and sometimes bleakly funny. Their siftings among the ashes of totalitarianism are apt preparation for a re-examination of Orwell&#39;s life and times. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> George Orwell&#39;s marriage, the unlikely life of an early Hollywood star, the man who changed American folk music and more.</p></div></div><p> In 2017, Ms. Funder began rereading Orwell and was captured anew by his mission to make an art of political writing. She fell again for his spiky humor, his rigorous anger, the tolling clarity of his sentences. She worked her way through the biographies published between 1972 and 2003, all written by men, and wondered why they minimized the importance of the women in Orwell&#39;s life, notably his wife Eileen. She came upon a diary entry from early 1949, during Orwell&#39;s last illness, about the “incorrigible dirtiness” of women and their “terrible, devouring sexuality.” How was it possible that this champion of the common man harbored such disgust for the common woman? The biographies offered no suitable explanations. “This is how I moved from the work to the life,” she writes, “and from the man to the wife.”</p><p> When the couple first met in 1935, he was a struggling novelist and journalist in London. Eileen had never heard of him, either by his pen name “George Orwell” or his given name of Eric Blair. Instead of getting a university education, he had spent five years in Burma as a colonial policeman, returning to England with a lifelong hatred for hierarchies of every kind and determination to become a writer. Eileen had been an honors student at Oxford, where her tutors included JRR Tolkien and CS Lewis, and was pursuing a master&#39;s degree in psychology. She chucked her career plans to marry Orwell in 1936 and went off to live with him in a 16th-century cottage in Hertfordshire, an hour or so north of London.</p><p> Orwell&#39;s ambitions became Eileen&#39;s as well: to escape what he called “the money-god” through rural self-sufficiency, keeping goats and chickens and planting a vegetable garden, coping with a primitive oven and an overflowing cesspool. He would write books while she would put her energy and talents into serving as his cook, housekeeper, typist, editor, publishing liaison and all-around facilitator. It was a hopeful time, and they were happy.</p><p> At the end of 1936, Orwell went to Spain to fight with the Republicans in the civil war. Eileen followed a few months later. Here Ms. Funder flips Orwell&#39;s classic 1938 account, “Homage to Catalonia,” to place Eileen instead of Orwell in the story&#39;s central role. In “Homage,” Orwell suggests that Eileen was standing by in a Barcelona hotel to send him little luxuries at the front and type up the observations he was sending her. In fact, she was also working as a high-level secretary in the offices of the Britain-based Independent Labour Party, which was infested with Stalinist spies. Ms. Funder combines the facts with imagined passages about Eileen&#39;s emotional state, along with personal observations from Ms. Funder&#39;s own trip to Barcelona to retrace the action. Such formal risks would be disastrous in the hands of a writer with less tact. But they&#39;re successful here, illuminating Eileen&#39;s bravery as she navigated an atmosphere thick with deceit and danger.</p><p> The Orwells spent most of the remaining seven years of their marriage trying to outrun or ignore serious illness: for him, the worsening tuberculosis that he refused to believe he had; for her, the chronic uterine bleeding that left her weak and anemic. Between spells in hospitals and sanatoriums, they carried on, always just scraping by, exhausting themselves with overwork. In addition to books, Orwell wrote mountains of reviews and took editorial jobs for magazines and at the BBC. When war broke out in 1939, Eileen worked as a secretary first at the Ministry of Information and later at the Ministry of Food. She continued to type, edit and contribute to the planning of Orwell&#39;s books; together in bed, they giggled over a little barnyard satire he was concocting. They refused to leave London during the Blitz, dodging bombs and moving house when their ramshackle flats were destroyed.</p><p> Illness and war stepped up Orwell&#39;s impulsiveness. He had never been faithful to Eileen, but now he pursued other women with a near-desperate fervor. Most scholars maintain, with insufficient evidence, that Eileen also had affairs; Ms. Funder has her doubts. Either way, although she was unhappy about Orwell&#39;s infidelities, Eileen never considered leaving him. At his insistence in 1944 they adopted a baby boy, Richard, and hoped eventually to adopt a girl. When Eileen died suddenly on the operating table in March 1945 at age 39, Orwell was absent. He had gone to Europe on assignment as a war correspondent and was enduring another health crisis in a military hospital in Germany when he got the news. Stubbornly reticent, he told a friend that he needed to leave because he had “things to do at home” and would return in a fortnight, which he did.</p><p> In the five years left to him, Orwell at last saw his financial anxieties ease when his barnyard satire, “Animal Farm,” was a surprise hit. Success had come too late for Eileen and was nearly too late for Orwell, who wrote “Nineteen Eighty-Four” between bouts of fever, typing the final draft when he was near total collapse. In a London hospital three months before his death he married a much younger woman, Sonia Brownell, making it clear that he needed a literary executor more than a wife. He was 47 when he died in 1950.</p><p> Ms. Funder clearly believes that Eileen&#39;s role in Orwell&#39;s life has been undervalued, her brilliance and valor underestimated. She balks at the ways Orwell views “women—as wives—in terms of what they do for him, or &#39;demand&#39; of him.” His exalted status, she implies, has obscured how tyrannical this hater of tyrannies could be, how insensitive he was toward the woman who best understood him.</p><p> Ms. Funder insists that she still loves Orwell and doesn&#39;t want to use Eileen as a cudgel to beat him with; yet often she can&#39;t seem to resist. “Wifedom” is most effective when she struggles away from judgment and stretches toward sympathy, as she does in her final pages. Whether sanctifying or demonizing, judgment is a limited tool if the goal is truly to see a committed partnership in all its ambiguity and incoherence, because judgment is always at least as much about the judge. At her best, Ms. Funder shows that radical compassion—which is not the same as forgiveness—will move one closer to understanding, in marriage and biography, every time.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。 Rifkind is the author of “The Sun and Her Stars: Salka Viertel and Hitler&#39;s Exiles in the Golden Age of Hollywood.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 16:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wifedom-review-orwell-a-portrait-of-her-marriage-fb31ab2c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wifedom-review-orwell-a-portrait-of-her-marriage-fb31ab2c<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Society/Community</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Marriage/Divorce</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>society</category><category> community</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>marriage</category><category> divorce</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>